description: From Latin obsolescere (“to wear out, fall into disuse, grow old, decay”), inceptive of obsolere (“to wear out, decay”) (rare), apparently from ob (“before”) + solere (“to be wont”); or else from obs-, a form of ob- + olere (“to grow”) (compare adolescent).

verbs.description: obsolesce (third-person singular simple present obsolesces, present participle obsolescing, simple past and past participle obsolesced)
